(6885, 4223, 'show_desc', 'EXCLUSIVE SPECIAL\r\n<div class="break"></div>\r\nIt was 1952 and polio had reached outbreak levels in America. There was no known cause, no cure, and no help in sight for parents desperate to protect their children. The country''s hope was placed in a 33-year-old scientist who was working from a basement lab in Pittsburgh. His name was Jonas Salk, and in just a few years, he would bring infantile paralysis to its knees and change the course of medical history. Travel back to a world gripped in fear and see how Dr. Salk, his dedicated staff, a young charity, and a faithful nation, came together to conquer polio.'),
